<br>
Note that all of it is drawn from memory having read the series multiple times as well as taking a look at some of the histories like the Silmarillion etc. That said its not guaranteed to be 100% accurate - if you see something that is not right be sure to let me know <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Finally, this contains <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>no spoilers about the films</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. While I will reference characters from it, nothing of the main story will be given away. You can freely read this without worrying about ruining the virgin experience of the films.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Of Morgoth and Sauron</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Morgoth is one of the Valar. The Valar are a sort of demi-god bunch who helped build the world from Song (actually this may not be 100% correct, but eh is close enough, the Valar may be the servants of the creators). Unfortunately Morgoth's Song was dissonant because he's a bit of a nasty horrible, and hence the world when created was infected with evil.<br>
<br>
Morgoth ran amok for a long time. Eventually, a very very (like thousands of years) long time ago he was beaten back by the combined forces of middle-Earth in a huge fight, after which all the Valar and most of the Elder races (elves etc) buggered off over the Sea to Valinor, the eternal home etc. <br>
<br>
His agent and right hand man Sauron however remained in the world.<br>
<br>
Since then Sauron has been a pain, causing strife and generally representing the forces of evil in the world. The Balrog was a creature of Morgoth that somehow survived under Moria for a very long time.<br>
<br>
Anyway, Sauron is still around. He became the nastiest little bastard on the face of Middle-Earth and created the Orcs by twisting and manipulating the elves (same thing that Inny did to the Elves in Norrath to make his Dark Elves).<br>
<br>
More of Sauron in the section about the Rings of Power, pretty much all of the sections since he has been pivotal in all of the major events of the world following the fall of Morgoth.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Of the Elves</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Note that Tolkien deliberately mispells the plural form of elfs and dwarfs. In the original edition of LOTR this was &quot;corrected&quot; by editors. A lot of supposed grammar and spelling mistakes were corrected and have had to be undone in a long drawn out process from the original manuscripts. The latest editions that have been extensively worked by his son Christopher and are pretty damn close to the original intent.<br>
<br>
Oh yeh, elves. Children of the Valar, they are the firstborn and cherished. They are basically immortal unless killed, Elrond for instance was present in the original war against Sauron way back in the day. Without spoiling things, if you watch the intro carefully in the Fellowship you'll see what I mean <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
There are two basic families of elves at the end of the Third Age (the time of the movies). High Elves live in Rivendell, and Wood Elves live in Mirkwood and Lothlorien. Their magic while potent is very subtle and usually enables them to do things like camoflage, stealth, healing and restoration, as well as physical feats like being able to run across the top of snow without sinking in etc.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Lembas</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the staple diet of the travelling elf is very nourishing and can keep a person on their feet for a long time, although if it is used as the traveller's core food for a very long time it can leave the eater feeling a little bit stretched and desiring other foods. Tastes magnificent <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The Elves in Middle-Earth at the end of the Third Age are a remnant of a remnant of the race. Most have passed over the Sea to the blessed fields of Valinor. The passing of Third Age marks the end of the time of the Elder races.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Of the Dwarves</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Either Tolkien was not forthcoming about their origin or I don't recall. I vaguelly remember something about one of the Valar, having seen the creation of the Elves, wanting a race of their own people and went underground for Dwarves. Unlike the Elves, Dwarves do not generally go over the Sea to Valinor, and are not immortal although rather long lived.<br>
<br>
The Dwarves of old had a massive underground kingdom in the Mountains of Mist where Moria now stands, from memory called Khazad-Dum. There they mined for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>mithril</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, a wondrous metal used for everything from jewelry to the finest and most precious armour known, light and incredibly strong.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately they dug too deep and uncovered some nasties from the time of Morgoth and that sort of ended Khazad-Dum. They have another city at the Lonely Mountain way over the Mountains of Mist and past the Mirkwood that was destroyed by the dragon Smaug, and reclaimed in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Hobbit</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Balin, Thorin and a bunch of dwarves, Gandalf and most notably the hobbit Bilbo Baggins. <br>
<br>
It was on this journey that Bilbo found the One Ring. More on that later.<br>
<br>
Dwarves are hardy fighters, strong and true tending to use axes and the like. They have little love for Men, and less for Elves.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Of Numenor and Men</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Numenor was a land to the East, a large island (? pretty sure) kingdom between Middle-Earth and Valinor. The greatest of Men lived there and created wonders. This was the highest time in the history of Men. Unfortunately they listened to the advice of Sauron who was at that time not revealed as an agent of Morgoth and everything went to hell.<br>
<br>
With the betrayal over the forging of the Rings of Power (see below) Numenor was destroyed and the refugees landed in Middle-Earth. The race of Men flourished for a time, creating the kingdom of Gondor to the west of where Mordor now stands. Always have the Men of Gondor been the first and heaviest hit by Sauron, they can be best considered as like to Borderland folk (Shienar etc) for those who have read the Wheel of Time.<br>
<br>
Anyway Men diminshed. Once able to live for many centuries, the blood of Numenor thinned and became mixed with that of lesser men until the people of the West lived only as long as real people do. Over this time the kingdom of Rohan, the horse Lords, was born to the East of Gondor. Ergoth to the North near the Shire and where Bree now stands was a part of Gondor, but most of that was destroyed in one or other of the wars against Sauron.<br>
<br>
There does however remain a hint of the old blood of Numenor, in the people of the Dunedin (sp?) who are the Rangers of the North. They protect what remains of Ergoth from monsters and orcs and the like, and Aragorn is of them (their leader I think).<br>
<br>
But I jump ahead. The most recent war against Sauron (not including the one told in the books) saw the One Ring cut from the hand of Sauron by Isildur, the king of Gondor. It was his undoing and hence came to be known by Men as Isildur's Bane - he was killed by orcs when the Ring betrayed him and was lost in a River .. forget the name, maybe it was the Anduin. The Ring has a mind of its own, and wants to get back to Sauron - no doubt it saw being the possession of a strong Numenorean king to be a bit of a dead end.<br>
<br>
Anyway that pretty much smashed the people of Gondor. They had no King and instead a line of Stewards was created to rule the cities. Kings are important to people in Middle-Earth, without one the race kind of dwindled quite a bit. An heir to the throne was hidden away with the Dunedin for some reason I could never quite understand and the line eventually came to Ranger Aragorn. I'm pretty sure its no secret that he is the heir to the throne of Gondor.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Of the Rings of Power</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Three Rings for the Elven Kings<br>
Under the sky<br>
Seven for the Dwarf Lords<br>
In their Halls of Stone<br>
Nine for the mortal Men<br>
Doomed to die<br>
One for the Dark Lord on his dark throne<br>
In the land of Mordor where the shadows lie<br>
One Ring to rule them all<br>
One Ring to find them<br>
One Ring to bring them all<br>
And in the darkness bind them<br>
In the land of Mordor where the shadows lie</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Cool huh? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Anyway, the elves - probably with the help of the dwarves, I don't recall - made their Three Rings. Sauron had nothing to do with the making of them, although he recognised their power immediately. The Elven Rings provide endurance, wisdom and strength, their magic subtle in the way of Elves.<br>
<br>
The Three have never been touched by Sauron and remain in the world. Its a bit of a spoiler to say who has them so I won't <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The Dwarves forged their Seven, Rings of power that from memory granted riches and in some manner helped with Dwarf-things like mining and finding mithril and probably drinking and singing etc. OK that last bit is a lame joke but you get the idea <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  The Seven are lost, consumed by dragons, lost in the belly of Khazad-Dum, or held by Sauron.<br>
<br>
Men jumped on the bandwagon and forged Nine Rings of Power. Unfortunately Sauron had a hand in it - remember he was a trusted advisor in Numenor then -  and used his influence to learn the making of Rings.<br>
<br>
In Mordor at Mount Doom Sauron forged the One Ring. The One is the most powerful, and most of Sauron's power went into its creation. Without it he is wraith-like, with little ability to influence the world directly, even though he holds the Nine. Oh yeh he did that, took the Nine and used them to warp their holders, Lords and Kings of Numenor all, into the Ringwraiths, the Black Riders.<br>
<br>
The One Ring is the big boy. It binds the others, most of all the Nine and least of all the Three, but their fates are bound up with it. Should the One be destroyed, all that was created by the Seven Nine and Three will fade and fall, and the power of the others will dwindle and die.<br>
<br>
That will do for now, if you have any questions let me know, yeh I'm a LOTR gimp but eh <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><center>
