<br>
The Valar is the title for all those created by the Illúvitar.<br>
<br>
The gods that were created by the Illúvitar include:<br>
The wizards* (The istari): Sauruman the White, Gandalf the Grey, Radagast the Brown, Pallando the Blue, and Alatar the Blue.<br>
<br>
The first three Istari governed Middle Earth, the last two were bound to Valinor and only briefly stepped foot upon the Western shores of Middle Earth...Near the Realm of Arnor, actually.<br>
<br>
Secondly, the Illúvitar created the Maiar:<br>
<br>
The Maiar are the shapeless governing bodies. They can be interpreted as the forces of nature, and other things that influence all the races of Earth. Such includes Morgoth and Sauruman.<br>
<br>
Be informed that Maiar have no names until they stray from their destined path...And such have they.<br>
<br>
And thirdly, the Eledhwen, the Elves:<br>
Immortal by age, not by force. Cherished, et. al.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Evil arises:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Morgoth, actually called himself Melkor until the Elves gave him such a title. He was also responsible for bringing Sauron with him. They were both good at one time.<br>
<br>
Morgoth stayed as the invisible hand of evil. Sauron himself took a form, many forms.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Ages:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The First Age</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can be marked as the Age of Creation. When the Illúvitar had created the races of Middle Earth. However this Age was brought to a climax as an Allegiance of Men and Elves marched across where the Dead Marshes now stand along the western borders of Mordor, along the Ephel Dúath. Sauron took the form of a wolf, a Warg, as they're called...And unleashed a great army of Orcs and Trolls unto the Men of Gondor and Rohan. The Warg was slain, however as Sauron has no real shape...You cannot kill him, just the form he carries. Only the undoing of the ring can bring about his death.<br>
In this period, Morgoth had taken on the powers of creation. In mimicry of Elves, the Orcs were devised. That is why they hold the tipped ears of Elven-kind. However all the traits of Elves are lessened in Orcs...But they are nevertheless keen-sensed.<br>
In mimicry of the Ents, the Trolls were created. Two forms. Trolls, and then the Olog-Hai. The Olog-Hai are day-marching Trolls, and they were bred specifically for assaulting southern Mirkwood and controlling the Black Gates. The other Trolls were more inquisitive, but altogether nasty folk that took to caves as powers of the night. Also, the Balrogs were created. These nasty creatures were devised in the image of the Istari, and were the strongest of all beings. The ending of the First Age saw many Balrogs created...And many were slain by the three Istari until one lay left, buried and hidden by Morgoth in Moria. Down the Endless Stair at an unreachable peak of the mighty Caradhras...And into the depths of the world where no being would touch until the Third age, as the Dwarves delved deeper in search of Mithril. The end of the First Age is marked by Sauron's first death.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Second Age</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can be marked as the Age of Unrest. It finds its continuation in the errant ways of Morgoth and Sauron. It is marked by the Valinorian Exodus, wherein many millions of Elves left for the Undying Lands.<br>
But upon the plains of Dagorlad, to the north of Mordor along the borders of the Ered Lithui mountains at the Black Gates (Morannon)...The remaining Elves and Men strove to quash another Evil rising. Clad as a would a human be, Sauron in plate-armor of black strode forth from the Black Gates to meet the Allied Forces. As Elendil strode forth to slay Sauron with Narsil, so was he dismissed by a mighty swing of the mace. As Man and Elf alike fell prey to the mighty swings of the Warmace of Barad-Dûr, Isildur rushed to his fallen father. The cloven Sword was hefted by Isildur, now king by way of force...With a mighty swing, the Shards of Narsil castrated the One from Sauron's body. As the ring is the Essence of Sauron's being, Sauron returned to his Celestial form. So ended the Second age and began the Third...Which you're all seeing now in the wonderful movies.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Of the Eledhwen, Immortal Children of the Illúvitar:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Gondolin<br>
Mirkwood<br>
Lothlórien<br>
Rivendell<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Gondolin</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was in the North, roughly where Mount Gundabad now lies. Falling in the very beginnings of the second by an assault of Balrogs. Not much is known about Gondolin, save their king was Turgon...And to mark his passing, Glamdring was forged. Glamdring was lost in the ruins of Gondolin...And out of the ruins of Gondolin Mount Gundabad was formed. A mighty kingdom of rocked was tumbled and covered with millenia of sands and dusts to form these mountains. It was within this mountain that Bert the Troll was hiding with Glamdring. Very precious this sword, but Bert found it shiny and entertaining...Sparkling. He found it to be easy on the ears, although the metal stung his hands. However Gandalf found the sword in this Troll cave in many of his wanderings...And he bequeathed it to Elrond, rightful owner, and heir to Gondolin.<br>
<br>
Not much is to be said of the rest of the Elves, for their history is rather peaceful, and altogether uninteresting for those not so inclined.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Of the men</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
<br>
